  "riddle": "1. Seek the obscure Detroit catcher whose seed page opens this hunt; read its opening and note the major-league club he played for and the years he appeared for them.\n\n2. There exists a simple cipher for your next move: take the first letter of the team name you just wrote down and convert it to its position in the alphabet (A = 1, B = 2, and so on).\n\n3. Which season-article for that club's 1978 campaign (follow the \"Article\" link from the seed page) describes the city — report how many metres above sea level Detroit sits.\n\n4. If you follow the roster or notable-players links to the slugger who starred for Detroit in the 1930s, record the total number of career home runs credited to that Hall-of-Famer.\n\n5. The page you reached links to the Tigers' beloved longtime right fielder — identify that outfielder's age at death as given on his article.\n\n6. Narratively: the catcher whose surname is also a common support structure spent his entire major-league career with a single club; name that team and the span of years he was with them.\n\n7. Metaphorically speaking, transform a hot number: what does 85 degrees Celsius become on the Fahrenheit scale if you multiply by 1.8 and discard any fractional part of the result?\n\n8. (As an aside) take the whole number you obtained in the previous clue and count how many '1' bits appear when that integer is written in binary.\n\n9. Follow a link or search to the Phillies' Hall-of-Fame third baseman famed for his power and record how many career home runs that slugger hit.\n\n10. Discover the conversion of 85 metres into yards by applying the metres→yards multiplier and truncating any fractional remainder; record the integer yardage.\n\n11. Now take that yardage integer and tally the number of ones in its binary expansion; that count is your next numeric clue.\n\n12. To continue, visit the page for the left-handed slugger who amassed over six hundred career home runs and report his lifetime batting average as